observations.recommendation:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated General Services Officer towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of all Inventory Accounts to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials; 

 The Municipal Accountant and designated General Services Officer maintain the prescribed ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each type of Inventory, keep track the actual Supplies Inventory on hand and reconcile the balances of the two inventory records;

The LCE require the concerned personnel to conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies and materials which shall be reported in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and

Based on the RPCI, the Municipal Accountant compute for the costs of the remaining Inventory using the Moving Average Method, which shall be reconciled with the balance of Inventory accounts in the financial statements.

The Municipal Accountant evaluate the need for those unexpended fund balances from NGAs, if the funds be proven to be no longer needed, these should be returned to the source agencies or else transfer the balances from TF to GF as prescribed in Section 3.2 of the COA Circular 2012-001;

 The Municipal Treasurer’s Office prepare the disbursement voucher for the refund of the unutilized funds for return to the SAs once the funds be proven to be no longer needed; and

The management monitor the status of funds and the implementation of the programs/projects and promptly submit the liquidation reports and documents for a refund of the unutilized balance.

Implement the development projects programmed during the year as embodied in the Annual Investment/Development Plan and ensure optimum utilization of the 20 percent Development Fund in compliance with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 for the benefit of the constituents of the Municipality;

Mobilize the concerned offices in the early planning and implementation of development projects to avoid incurring possible additional cost as a result of delayed implementation; and 

At the end of each year, review all unimplemented projects and verify whether they can be implemented in the succeeding year. All savings from completed projects and all projects which are no longer feasible and cannot be implemented should be considered for immediate realignment, subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20 percent Development Fund for re-appropriation to other development projects.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated General Services Officer towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of all Inventory Accounts to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;
The Municipal Accountant and designated General Services Officer maintain the prescribed ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each type of Inventory, keep track the actual Supplies Inventory on hand and reconcile the balances of the two inventory records;
The LCE require the concerned personnel to conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies and materials which shall be reported in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and
Based on the RPCI, the Municipal Accountant compute for the costs of the remaining Inventory using the Moving Average Method, which shall be reconciled with the balance of Inventory accounts in the financial statements.

The Inventory Committee complete the inventory taking of PPE and come up with a comprehensive and reliable RPCPPE for reconciliation; 

The Accounting and the Property Units undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled in order to come up with a duly reconciled PPE balances; and

The Municipal Mayor, Inventory Committee, Property Unit, Accounting Unit and concerned municipal government department heads and concerned employees be mindful of their respective share of compliance on the specific guidelines as to preliminary activities prior to the conduct of inventory taking, the inventory taking itself and reconciliation of PPE, in order to accomplish the main objective of cleansing the PPE of the Municipality.

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all claims for Fuel, Oil and Lubricants are supported with complete documents required under COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977, to enable the Audit Team to further validate the claims and to avoid the issuance of Notice of Suspension/Disallowance;

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) through the General Services Office shall implement control over the use of government vehicle through properly accomplished and duly approved and serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets, a summary of which shall be made at the end of each month in a Monthly Report of Official Travels for audit purposes; and

Monthly Report on Fuel Consumption and Monthly Report of Official Travels shall likewise be prepared and submitted to the Office of the Auditor for verification purposes to determine the reasonableness of the fuel consumed during the period.

Management should strictly require all collectors to turnover their collections to the Municipal Treasurer daily and intact pursuant Section 29 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I, in order to avoid the risk of loss or improper use;

The Municipal Treasurer should strictly monitor the issuance of accountable forms to the collectors by seeing to it that accountable forms issued to collectors are fully issued and collections thereof are fully remitted before a new stub is issued to them;

The Municipal Treasurer deposit her collections regularly and intact and discontinue the practice of retaining/withholding part of her collections pursuant to Section 69(4) of P. D. 1445 and Section 32 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I, to ensure the safety and avoid risk of loss of government funds; and 

Management impose disciplinary actions or sanctions when necessary, in order to enforce compliance with the existing rules and regulations on collection, reporting and remittances and in order to safeguard government funds.

The MDRRMC ensure that the proposed Programs, Projects and Activities (PPAs) chargeable against the LDRRMF are strictly related for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation and recovery; 

Management ensure optimum utilization of the calamity fund for expenditures that address the key objectives of disaster risk reduction and management as envisioned under R.A. No. 10121; and

Revert to the LDRRM Fund the amount of P0.626 million that were erroneously charged against the fund which shall be reappropriated to finance only those programs, projects, and activities identified to be funded under the 5% LDRRM fund for the ensuing year.

Strengthen internal control system on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by regularly performing periodic reconciliation of the accounting records, property records and the result of the actual inventory;

Subsidiary Ledger Cards and Property Cards for each group of PPEs shall be maintained by the Accounting Office and General Services Offices, respectively; 

Unserviceable properties and equipment shall be inspected, disposed and dropped from the books of accounts following the guidelines set forth in Section 79 of PD 1445 and Section 59 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II; and

Strictly adhere to existing laws, rules and regulations on property and supply management in order to safeguard government properties from loss, destruction and deterioration.

a.  The Municipal Accountant exerts extra effort to review the long outstanding/stale checks and secure the addresses of the payees for notification of the return of the stale checks in their possession for replacement;

b.  The Municipal Treasurer cancels the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the Municipal Accountant with the original Disbursement Vouchers (DV) together with its supporting documents, for the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher following the procedures prescribed to ensure the recording of such cancellation;

c.  The Municipal Accountant periodically coordinates with the Municipal Treasurer regarding the existence of stale checks;

d.  For those stale checks whose payees could no longer be located and if per record, these have been staled for many years; consider the reversion of these payables to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund; and

e.  Henceforth, require the Municipal Treasurer to send a written notice to the payee of the existence of the check at least one month before the check becomes stale as required in Section 59 of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS).

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Management creates an Inventory Committee purposely for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The Inventory Committee shall have at least one member from the Accounting and Property Division as required by COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
The Property and Accounting Units undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPLCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.  The reconciliation shall be completed within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee;
Conduct disposal of unserviceable PPEs, if there is any, by accomplishing the required Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties pursuant to Annex 51 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs which will serve as the basis in dropping said items in the RPCPPE and books of accounts;
If accountability/responsibility over missing PPEs could not be pinpointed after investigation, authority for derecognition thereof from the books of accounts may be requested from the COA, in accordance with Paragraph 8 of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
A Municipal Valuation Committee be created to determine the appraised value of donated properties and those properties found on station during the inventory taking so that these properties can be correctly recorded in the books of accounts of the municipality; and
Henceforth, Management adheres to existing laws, rules and regulations on property and supply management and safeguard government properties from loss, destruction and deterioration.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following;
Direct the Solid Waste Focal Person to immediately transport the said solid waste to the MRF of the Municipality so that the Commercial Center can start operating;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to inspect the structure to determine immediate repairs to be done in order to make the Commercial Center operational;
Immediately operationalize the Commercial Center so that revenues can be earned/generated to finance other development projects of the LGU; and
Assign personnel to conduct routine maintenance and inspection activities in order to prevent undue deterioration and damage to the facility.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Exert prudence in the disbursement of the LDRRMF and immediately stop the charging of monthly wages of municipal job hires against the LDRRM Fund;
Strictly utilize the LDRRM Fund for the projects/activities enumerated in Section 5 of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG Joint Circular No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013 dated and NDRRMC, DILG, DBM and CSC Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2014-1 dated April 4, 2014, to avoid issuance Notice of Suspensions or Disallowances;
Revert to the LDRRM Fund the amount of P2.446 million representing disbursements for payment of wages of municipal job hires in CY 2021 that were erroneously charged against the fund which shall be re-appropriated to finance only those programs, projects and activities identified to be funded under the 5% LDRRM Fund for the ensuing year.

